answers.body_markdown:
The issue typescript sees here is that `p.values` and `p.value` are mutually exclusive by your type definition. Instead, consider the following typing:

    type Props =
      | {
          isMulti: true;
          value: undefined
          values: string[];
        }
      | {
          isMulti: false;
          value: string;
          values: undefined
        };

Like this, TS will infer that value/values always exist as either their typing or as undefined(which is the default for a property that doesn&#39;t exist anyway) instead of being mutually exclusive. TS also infers their typings properly in the sense that if `isMulti` is true, `value` will be `undefined` as expected, for example.

An alternative would be to forgo the whole value/values aspect:

    type Props =
      | {
          isMulti: true;
          value: string[]
        }
      | {
          isMulti: false;
          value: string;
        };

in this case, you could just use `value` instead of having two attributes with similar names.

